-- Gold Futures Decline From Record as Dollar Rebound Spurs Investor Selling
-- B y   P h a m - D u y   N g u y e n
-- 2010-09-30T18:55:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-30/gold-futures-decline-from-record-as-dollar-rebound-spurs-investor-selling.html
Gold futures fell from a record as
the dollar halted a slide, eroding demand for the precious metal
as an alternative asset.  The greenback rose as much as 0.4 percent a basket of six
major currencies a Chicago purchasing managers’ survey was
higher than forecast and U.S. jobless claims unexpectedly fell.
Earlier, the dollar touched an eight-month low, and gold reached
a record $1,317.50 an ounce, posting an all-time high for the
10th time this month.  “Gold is taking its cue from the dollar,” said  Matthew Zeman , a metal trader at LaSalle Futures Group in Chicago.
“We’ve seen a reversal in the dollar and a little risk premium
is coming out of the gold trade.”  Gold futures for December delivery fell 70 cents to settle
at $1,309.60 an ounce at 2:06 p.m. on the Comex in New York.
Earlier, the price dropped as much as 1 percent.  The meal rose 4.7 percent this month. In the third quarter,
gold climbed 5.1 percent, the eighth straight quarterly gain.  The 14-day relative-strength index, a gauge of price
momentum, has been above 70 since Sept. 22, a signal to some
traders that the price is poised to decline.  “Gold is overbought at this point, but the market is
having a hard time selling off,” Zeman said. “This market
remains very strong and continues to be bought on dips.”  Gold has gained 19 percent this year, heading for the 10th
straight annual gain, on demand for an alternative to stocks and
bonds.  Some investors have turned to cheaper alternatives after
gold surged, analysts said.  Silver, Platinum  “Investors are clearly shifting their focus to precious
metals of a hybrid character,” Commerzbank AG said in a report.
“These firstly have the status of a safe haven, but also show
some correlation with the economic cycle. Silver, platinum and
also palladium should therefore remain well supported.”  Silver futures for December delivery fell 13.1 cents, or
0.6 percent, to $21.821 an ounce. Earlier, the metal reached
$22.125, the highest level since October 1980. In September, the
price gained 12 percent, the most since November 2009. The
commodity was up 17 percent in the third quarter, the seventh
straight gain.  Platinum futures for January delivery rose $2, or 0.1
percent, to $1,658.60 an ounce on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. In September, the metal jumped 8.9 percent, the most
since November. The price gained 7.9 percent this quarter.  Palladium futures for December delivery rose $3.95, or 0.7
percent, to $571.25 an ounce. Earlier, the metal reached
$582.65, the highest level since March 2008. The price gained 14
percent this month and 29 percent in the third quarter.  To contact the reporter on this story:
